            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How the DC income tax calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This DC income tax calculator estimates your District of
                Columbia individual income tax based on the published
                progressive tax brackets, your filing status, deductions, and an
                approximation of common DC credits. It is designed to be
                transparent: you can see the tax owed in each bracket and how
                your marginal and effective tax rates are derived.
              </p>

              <h3>Step 1 – Start from DC adjusted gross income (AGI)</h3>
              <p>
                Begin with your <strong>DC adjusted gross income (AGI)</strong>.
                For most residents this is similar to federal AGI, with
                DC-specific additions and subtractions. You can use:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Your latest DC return (Form D-40) as a reference, or</li>
                <li>
                  An estimate based on your wages, self-employment income, and
                  other taxable income.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Step 2 – Subtract deductions</h3>
              <p>
                DC allows either a <strong>standard deduction</strong> or
                <strong>itemized deductions</strong> (if they exceed the
                standard and are allowed by DC law).
              </p>
              <p>In this calculator you can choose between:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Standard deduction</strong> – the default, based on
                  your filing status.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Itemized deductions</strong> – enter your total
                  DC-allowable itemized amount.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Taxable income formula</p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{DC taxable income} = \max\bigl(0,\; \text{DC AGI} -
                  \text{deductions}\bigr) \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Step 3 – Apply DC progressive tax brackets</h3>
              <p>
                DC uses a <strong>progressive</strong> tax system: different
                portions of your taxable income are taxed at different rates.
                Conceptually:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \[ \text{DC tax before credits} = \sum_{\text{each bracket}}
                  \bigl(\text{taxable income in bracket}\bigr) \times
                  \text{bracket rate} \]
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The calculator automatically splits your taxable income across
                the brackets for the selected year and filing status and shows
                the dollar amount taxed in each band in the “Bracket breakdown”
                panel.
              </p>

              <h3>Step 4 – Subtract DC credits</h3>
              <p>
                DC offers a variety of <strong>nonrefundable</strong> and
                <strong>refundable</strong> credits, such as:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>DC Earned Income Tax Credit (EITC)</li>
                <li>Child and dependent care credit</li>
                <li>Property tax and renter credits</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Because eligibility and amounts depend on many factors, this
                calculator lets you enter an
                <strong>estimated total of DC credits</strong>. These are
                subtracted from the tax before credits:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \[ \text{DC tax after credits} = \max\bigl(0,\; \text{tax
                  before credits} - \text{DC credits}\bigr) \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Marginal vs. effective DC tax rate</h3>
              <p>The calculator reports two key rates:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Marginal tax rate</strong> – the rate that applies to
                  your <em>last</em> dollar of taxable income (the highest
                  bracket you reach).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Effective tax rate</strong> – your total DC tax
                  divided by your DC AGI: \[ \text{Effective rate} =
                  \frac{\text{DC tax after credits}}{\text{DC AGI}} \]
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Your effective rate is always lower than your marginal rate
                because only the top portion of your income is taxed at the
                highest rate.
              </p>

              <h2>DC income tax brackets (overview)</h2>
              <p>
                For each tax year, DC law (D.C. Code § 47‑1806.03 and related
                guidance) defines income ranges and rates. The calculator
                includes an up-to-date approximation of those brackets for:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Single</strong></li>
                <li><strong>Married filing jointly</strong></li>
                <li><strong>Married filing separately</strong></li>
                <li><strong>Head of household</strong></li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Exact thresholds and rates can change with legislation. Always
                confirm against the
                <a
                  href="https://otr.cfo.dc.gov/"
                  class="text-blue-600 hover:underline"
                  target="_blank"
                  rel="noopener"
                  >DC Office of Tax and Revenue</a
                >
                if you are filing a return.
              </p>

              <h2>Limitations and important notes</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  This tool is an <strong>educational estimator</strong>, not
                  official tax preparation software.
                </li>
                <li>
                  It does <strong>not</strong> handle every special DC provision
                  (e.g., part-year residency, nonresident income allocation,
                  certain business or trust income).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Credits are simplified as a single user-entered amount; actual
                  DC credits may be subject to income limits, phase-outs, and
                  separate calculations.
                </li>
                <li>
                  For complex situations, consult a qualified tax professional
                  or DC’s official instructions and forms.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions about DC income tax</h2>

              <h3>Do I have to file a DC income tax return?</h3>
              <p>
                In general, DC residents must file a return if their DC gross
                income is above the filing threshold for their filing status.
                Nonresidents with DC-source income may also have filing
                obligations. Check the latest instructions for Form D‑40 on the
                DC OTR website for current thresholds and exceptions.
              </p>

              <h3>Does DC tax capital gains and dividends?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. Most capital gains, dividends, and interest are included in
                DC adjusted gross income and taxed at the same rates as ordinary
                income, unless a specific exclusion applies.
              </p>

              <h3>How is DC income tax different from federal income tax?</h3>
              <p>
                DC starts from federal AGI but has its own deductions,
                exemptions, credits, and tax brackets. Your DC tax liability
                will almost never be the same as your federal tax, even if your
                income is identical.
              </p>

              <h3>
                Can this calculator handle part-year residents or multiple
                states?
              </h3>
              <p>
                This calculator is focused on
                <strong>DC resident</strong> returns and does not allocate
                income across multiple states. If you moved in or out of DC
                during the year, you may need to prorate income and deductions
                according to DC rules and possibly file in other states as well.
              </p>

              <h3>Is the result here enough to file my DC tax return?</h3>
              <p>
                No. The result is an estimate only. You should complete the
                official DC forms (or use professional tax software) and keep
                documentation for all income, deductions, and credits you claim.
              </p>
